\begin_layout Abstract
\noindent
This paper describes the development and validation of a converter that, starting from a MATPOWER description of an electric power network, generates a nonlinear power flow model in the 
\emph on
current balance formulation in polar coordinates
\emph default
, intended to be solved in the dTwin environment. The converter is implemented as a C++ plugin for dTwin (natID framework), with the conversion running in a separate worker thread, real-time progress reporting and a graphical interface. The theoretical background of the formulation, the architecture of the converter and a threefold validation on the WSCC 
\family typewriter
case9
\family default
 test system are presented: the admittance matrix matches the reference model to more than ten significant digits, the equation residuals at the exact solution are of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-13}$
\end_inset

, and the generated model is successfully solved by the built-in Newton–Raphson solver in four iterations.
\end_layout

