\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The power flow computation is the fundamental calculation in power system analysis: for a given network topology, branch parameters and power injections at the buses, one seeks the voltage magnitudes 
\begin_inset Formula $V_i$
\end_inset

 and phase angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_i$
\end_inset

 at all buses, and from them the branch power flows and losses. Practically all more advanced analyses rest on this computation — network expansion planning, state estimation, operational security analysis and optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "kundur,milano"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classically, the system of equations is formed through the 
\emph on
power balance
\emph default
: at every bus the active and reactive power mismatches (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta Q_i$
\end_inset

) must equal zero. An equivalent, but structurally different alternative is the 
\emph on
current balance
\emph default
 (current injection) formulation, in which the zero is sought in the mismatch of the complex bus current 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "cim"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. This work uses exactly that formulation, in 
\series bold
polar coordinates
\series default
: the unknowns remain 
\begin_inset Formula $V_i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_i$
\end_inset

, as in the classical polar Newton–Raphson procedure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "tinney"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but the equations are algebraically simpler because the voltage of the observed bus does not multiply the whole sum over the neighbouring buses.
\end_layout

