\begin_layout Section
Theoretical background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:teorija"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Network model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All quantities are expressed in per-unit (p.u.) with respect to the base power 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{base}$
\end_inset

. A branch is modelled by the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

-scheme: series impedance 
\begin_inset Formula $r+jx$
\end_inset

, total shunt susceptance 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (one half at each end) and, for transformer branches, a complex tap ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $a = t\,e^{j\varphi}$
\end_inset

 which covers both magnitude regulation (
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) and phase shift (
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

). Bus shunt elements (compensation) are given as 
\begin_inset Formula $G_s + jB_s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Admittance matrix (Y-bus)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The network is compactly described by the admittance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Y}$
\end_inset

, with the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}=\mathbf{Y}\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $I_i=\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k$
\end_inset

. For a branch 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

–
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 with series admittance 
\begin_inset Formula $y=1/(r+jx)$
\end_inset

 and shunt admittance 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{sh}=j\,b/2$
\end_inset

 the contributions to the admittance matrix read: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Y_{ff}\mathrel{+}=\frac{y+b_{sh}}{a\,a^{*}},\qquad
Y_{tt}\mathrel{+}=y+b_{sh},\qquad
Y_{ft}\mathrel{+}=-\frac{y}{a^{*}},\qquad
Y_{tf}\mathrel{+}=-\frac{y}{a}.
\label{eq:ybus}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Bus shunt elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_s+jB_s)$
\end_inset

 are added to the corresponding diagonal entry. For real networks the matrix is extremely sparse — the number of nonzero entries grows linearly with the number of branches. In polar form the entries are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{ik}=Y_{ik}e^{j\theta_{ik}}$
\end_inset

 and the voltages as 
\begin_inset Formula $V_k=V_k e^{j\delta_k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Current balance equations in polar coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current that bus 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 receives from the network is computed directly from the admittance matrix: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I_i^{calc}=\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k\,e^{j(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k)}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\Re\{I_i^{calc}\}=\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k\cos(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k),\qquad
\Im\{I_i^{calc}\}=\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k\sin(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k).
\label{eq:icalc}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

On the other hand, the current that the bus 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demands
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 follows from its specified apparent power 
\begin_inset Formula $S_i=P_i+jQ_i=V_iI_i^{*}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I_i^{sp}=\left(\frac{S_i}{V_i e^{j\delta_i}}\right)^{*}
        =\frac{P_i-jQ_i}{V_i}\,e^{j\delta_i}.
\label{eq:isp}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The balance condition 
\begin_inset Formula $I_i^{calc}=I_i^{sp}$
\end_inset

, separated into real and imaginary parts, yields two equations per bus: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k\cos(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k) &= \frac{P_i\cos\delta_i+Q_i\sin\delta_i}{V_i},
\label{eq:cbre}\\
\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k\sin(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k) &= \frac{P_i\sin\delta_i-Q_i\cos\delta_i}{V_i}.
\label{eq:cbim}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison with the power balance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classical active power balance equation reads 
\begin_inset Formula $V_i\sum_k Y_{ik}V_k\cos(\delta_i-\theta_{ik}-\delta_k)=P_i$
\end_inset

 (analogously for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_i$
\end_inset

). The difference with respect to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cbre"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cbim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 is structural: in the power balance the voltage of the observed bus 
\begin_inset Formula $V_i$
\end_inset

 multiplies the whole sum, so it appears in every term of the residual and in all derivatives; in the current balance the left-hand side is 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 in each 
\begin_inset Formula $V_k$
\end_inset

, and the nonlinearity in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_i$
\end_inset

 is confined to the right-hand side (the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/V_i$
\end_inset

 term). The residual and the Jacobian are therefore derived from 
\series bold
currents
\series default
, which simplifies the analytical derivatives and the implementation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "cim"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. Both formulations have the identical solution — one chooses between them according to implementation convenience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Newton–Raphson method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cbre"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cbim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x})=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 with the vector of unknowns 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=[\boldsymbol{\delta},\mathbf{V}]$
\end_inset

 and solved iteratively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "tinney"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{J}^{(\nu)}\,\Delta\mathbf{x}^{(\nu)}=-\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}^{(\nu)}),
\qquad
\mathbf{x}^{(\nu+1)}=\mathbf{x}^{(\nu)}+\Delta\mathbf{x}^{(\nu)},
\label{eq:nr}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{J}=\partial(\Delta I^{\Re},\Delta I^{\Im})/\partial(\boldsymbol{\delta},\mathbf{V})$
\end_inset

 is a sparse Jacobian with the same structure as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Y}$
\end_inset

. The off-diagonal derivatives follow directly from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:icalc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 and are particularly simple: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f_i^{\Re}}{\partial \delta_k}=-Y_{ik}V_k\sin(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k),
\qquad
\frac{\partial f_i^{\Re}}{\partial V_k}=Y_{ik}\cos(\theta_{ik}+\delta_k),
\qquad k\neq i,
\label{eq:jac}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

(analogously for 
\begin_inset Formula $f_i^{\Im}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\leftrightarrow\cos$
\end_inset

 swapped and the sign adjusted), while the diagonal terms additionally receive the contribution of the right-hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cbre"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cbim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

. The starting point is a flat start (
\begin_inset Formula $V_i=1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

p.u., 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_i=0$
\end_inset

), and the iterations stop when the largest residual falls below the prescribed tolerance. Near the solution the convergence is quadratic — the number of correct digits roughly doubles in every iteration, which is also confirmed experimentally in section
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:rezultati"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bus types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three standard bus types take part in the formulation (table
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
