\begin_layout Subsection
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:diskusija"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results confirm that the current balance formulation in polar coordinates yields a physically correct solution, identical to the classical power balance, with simpler analytical derivatives. The dense Y-bus representation is adequate for the target problem size; for networks with thousands of buses the natural extension is a sparse matrix structure and a sparse Jacobian. Further extensions include automatic enforcement of generator reactive power limits (PV
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

PQ switching), support for multiple voltage levels in the display, and conversion of larger MATPOWER cases (
\family typewriter
case39
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
case118
\family default
) for which the formulation remains unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:zakljucak"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A C++ plugin-converter has been implemented and validated which, from a MATPOWER network description, generates a dTwin NL power flow model in the nonlinear current balance formulation in polar coordinates. The theoretical part derives the balance equations and shows their structural advantage over the power balance; the implementation part covers the entire path from parsing to a model ready for solving. The threefold validation — Y-bus agreement to 10+ digits, residuals of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-13}$
\end_inset

 at the exact solution and successful solving of the model by the dTwin solver in four iterations — shows that the conversion introduces neither modelling nor numerical error. All requirements of the topic are fulfilled: C++, conversion in a separate thread, real-time progress on the GUI thread, a graphical interface and delivery as a plugin (dynamic library).
\end_layout

